    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>36B</citedRange></bibl>
                  (<bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2016"/>, <citedRange>§206</citedRange></bibl>;
                  <bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2017a"/>, <citedRange>59</citedRange></bibl>;
                  <bibl><ptr target="#Bonnechere2018"/>, <citedRange>§33 n. 106</citedRange></bibl>;
                  <bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2018a"/>, <citedRange>333 and 338 n. 17</citedRange></bibl> <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/> <citedRange>36B</citedRange>[last consulted 16/07/2026]</bibl>).
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                    <ab>
                        <lb n="1"/><rs type="deity" ref="#theos"><w lemma="θεός">θεός</w>·</rs> <rs type="deity" ref="#tyche"><w lemma="τύχα">τύχα</w></rs> <w lemma="ἀγαθά">ἀγαθά</w>· <persName><name nymRef="#Φιλοτίδος"><unclear>Φ</unclear>ιλοτίδος</name></persName> τὰ <w lemma="σιδάρια">σιδά<lb n="2" break="no"/>ρια</w> δικαίς;         
                </ab>
          </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>God. Good Fortune. Do the iron objects rightfully belong to Philotis?</p>
                </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
                <p>Dios. Buena Fortuna, ¿corresponden por derecho los objetos de hierro a Filótide?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>This private enquiry, which does not include the name of the consultant, belongs to the well-attested category of consultations concerning <rs type="theme" ref="#property">property matters</rs>, in this case the rightful ownership of <foreign xml:lang="grc">σιδάρια</foreign> by a woman named <persName><name nymRef="#Φιλοτίδος">Philotis</name></persName>; on legal disputes in the Dodona oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2018"/></bibl>. According to <bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2017a"/></bibl>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">σιδάρια</foreign> refers to iron objects and not to the Byzantine coinage <foreign xml:lang="grc">σιδάρεοι</foreign>, as proposed by the editors of <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/></bibl>.</p>
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#Chaniotis2018a"/></bibl> interprets the text as an oracular response. On the controversial issue of the presence of answers on the Dodona tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#MartínGonzález2021"/></bibl>.</p>
                 <p n="Ithaca Results">Ithaca predicts Italy, including Magna Graecia, as the most probable geographical origin of this inscription (73.35%), with Epirus ranking second (7.12%). Regarding chronology, the highest probability falls at the beginning of the 4th century BC, specifically in the period 400-390 BCE (14.64%). See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline36B_2026_06_25.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline36B.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline36B_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
        </div>
        </body>
